default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultWritten evidence submitted by the Local Government Association (LGA)default&#xa0;defaultAbout the Local Government Associationdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice of local government.  We work 
defaultwith councils to support, promote and improve local government.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and
default set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGA covers every part of England and Wales, supporting local government as the most efficient and accountable part of the
default public sector.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe welcome the opportunity to submit evidence to the Education Select Committee
default’s inquiry into the Department for Educations proposed reforms to the regulation of children’s homes.
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
default1.
default              
defaultResidential children’s homes are an 
defaultimportant and necessary part of our care system
default; for some children it will be the placement which best meets their needs.
default 
defaultHowever, 
defaultit 
defaultis clear that reform is needed in order to 
defaultimprove the system for the children who rely on them
default. 
defaultThis requires all parts o
defaultf the system to work more effectively, including councils and providers. It is important to note that while regulatory change can have some positive impact, it can only achieve so much; there are a wider set of issues that must a
defaultlso be considered
default.
default  
default&#xa0;
default2.
default              
defaultTh
defaulte market for children’s homes is complex.  It has been shaped over decades by historic factors and must also be viewed in the context of the wider system for children in care. There is mixed private, charitable and local authority provision with significan
defaultt clustering of homes in certain geographic areas. There needs to be a better balance of provision in order to meet the needs of children and yo
defaultung people across the country. 
defaultCouncils have a key role in making this happen, through more effective commission
defaulting, working with each other and providers to shape the market
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.
default              
defaultIn recognition of this, t
defaulthe LGA commissioned 
defaultthe Office for Public Management (OPM) t
defaulto carry out an action research project with ten local authorities and providers, looking at how to 
defaultachieve more effective strategic commissioning of children’s homes.
default 
defaultThe research focused on three aspects of commissioning: needs analysis; matching needs and supply; and quality assurance and monitoring.
default The final report, available 
defaulton the L
defaultGA’s website, 
defaultmakes 
defaultr
defaultecommendations for improvement
default and highlights a number of practic
defaultal
default examples
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultLocation of children
default’s placements
default and 
defaultof children’s 
defaulthome
defaults
default&#xa0;
default4.
default              
defaultThere are a number of changes
default proposed by the Department for Education
default which the LGA welcomes and considers would make a
default positive impact on the system.  These include
default the new duty on children’s homes to notify the authority for the area where they are located every time a child is admitted to a placement and when they are di
defaultscharged.  It is important that councils know which looked after children are living in homes in their area, in order 
default 
defaultthat they can effectively discharge their safeguarding duties and understand the impact on other local services.  
default&#xa0;
default5
default.
default              
defaultThe lack of this i
defaultnformation can be a source of frustration and concern for some ‘area’ authorities.  Although the council-to-council notification system should address this, as noted in the consultation document emergency placements sometimes leads to delay. Placing a para
defaultllel duty on children’s homes 
defaultwould
default therefore provide an additional safety net.  
default&#xa0;
default6
default.
default              
defaultAlthough we recognise that the system of 
default‘
defaultplacing
default’
default authorities notifying area authorities 
defaultneeds to be improved
default, we are concerned that the proposed change to require 
defaultthem
default to consult with ‘area’ councils before making a placement could be fraught with difficulties. For example, consultation implies joint agreement on a placement decision; there is potential for a situation to occur whereby the ‘area’ authority believes that
default the placement should
default not
default go ahead, but the placing authority disagrees and makes it anyway. It is not clear how this would be resolved. 
default&#xa0;
default7
default.
default              
defaultIn addition, 
defaultwe are concerned that 
defaultthere could be scope for ‘area’ authorities to be legally challenged by provide
defaultrs
default, based on the advice and information they provide to ‘placing’ authorities
default. How to achieve the objective of ensuring children are placed in appropriate areas and with access to other relevant local services 
defaulttherefore 
defaultneeds further consideration
default.
default&#xa0;
default8
default.
default              
defaultCou
defaultncils have safeguarding responsibilities for all children in their area, even if they are not the corporate parent
default and 
defaultt
defaulthere are concerns about 
defaulttheir 
defaultlack of control over independent providers establishing homes in their area.  This has contributed to the 
defaultgeographical clustering of homes, which means that supply of children’s homes is distorted and does not reflect demand across the country. This in turn contributes to 
defaultthe 
defaultnumbers of 
defaultchildren placed 
defaultout of
default their local
default area.  
default&#xa0;
default9
default.
default              
defaultSuch clustering also places significant burdens on other local services in those areas, for example schools or child and adolescent mental health provision.  The 
defaultsiting
default of many children’s homes in a small area can also itself have an impact on the safety o
defaultf the children.  We therefore welcome the Department’s attempt to address this.  
default&#xa0;
default10
default.
default              
defaultAlthough it is not possible to deem an area ‘safe’ or ‘unsafe’, due to the complex factors at play and how those change over time, we do agree that a responsibility on h
defaultomes to carry out an annual risk assessment and to do this in conjunction with relevant local services is sensible.  In addition, the assessment of risk should be accompanied by a plan setting out how those risks will be mitigated.  No area is risk free
default fo
defaultr vulnerable children
default; setting out how those risks will 
defaultbe 
defaulthandled is as important as identifying them.  
default&#xa0;
default11
default.
default              
defaultFollowing consultation with the police and children’
defaults
default services, p
defaultroviders should be required to provide both elements to 
defaultOfsted
default and to the 
defaultLocal 
defaultSafeguarding Children Board
default (LSCB)
default for the area where the home is located. If the exercise is to have any meaning, 
defaultOfsted
default must have sufficient power to refuse registration or to de-register homes where the risks cannot be sufficiently mitigated.  LSCBs sho
defaultuld also have the power to make a submission to 
defaultOfsted
default on the appropriateness of the risk assessment and the measures proposed to mitigate any risks based on their local knowledge; 
defaultOfsted
default should have a duty to have regard to such a submission. It is possib
defaultle that local services may consider that the provider has not sufficiently addressed a risk and it is important that 
defaultOfsted
default has all the relevant information to come to an informed decision. 
default&#xa0;
default12
default.
default              
defaultAs noted in the introduction to this submission, the challenge of ensuring a better match between provision and the needs of children across the country requires more than just regulatory change.  Councils and providers must work closely together, with cou
defaultncils giving a clear picture of need to give providers confidence to invest and providers giving a clearer picture of what services they are delivering. 
