defaultStatements of Purpose
default&#xa0;
default1
default3
default.
default              
defaultThe action research that the LGA commissioned OPM to carry out on the comm
defaultissioning of children’s homes 
defaultidentified
default that 
defaultbetter
default matching of needs with supply could help to reduce placement breakdown. 
defaultCouncils
default would generally welcome 
defaulta 
defaultdeeper understanding of the services available across the existing children’s residential home m
defaultarket. A common language to describe offers would help
default. C
defaultoncerns were raised throughout the research (including from providers) that inflated claims about services mean inappropriate placements are made and needs cannot be fulfilled. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default4
default.
default              
defaultNearly all parti
defaultcipants said more specialist provision is needed nationally and locally as 
defaultcouncils
default are struggling to match the most complex needs with supply. They also report that the number of children with multiple complex needs is increasing. 
defaultCouncils
default seek ‘specialis
defaultt’ and ‘therapeutic’ placements but
default,
default across the board (providers included)
default,
default said there is insufficient understanding amongst local authority commissioners and their partners about what this means in practice and insufficient evidence about what works and f
defaultor whom. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default5
default.
default              
defaultIn some authorities direct conversations between social work teams and commissioners have helped build 
defaulta 
defaultdeeper shared understanding of 
defaultthe offer from 
defaultprovider
defaults
default. Providers can also do more to articulate the services they offer and to demonstrate the staff and skills available to deliver services. The impact of a misjudged or ineffectual placement is so significant (for that individual child or young person and ot
defaulthers in the home, including staff) that there may 
defaultbe 
defaultjustification for more formal requirements around ethical advertising. The sector needs to more clearly define ‘specialist’ and ‘therapeutic’ care and promote the use of common language (amongst commissi
defaultoners and providers) to describe different type
defaults
default of provision.
default 
defaultOne of the recommendations of the report was that there is a tightening of children’s homes’ formal statement of purpose.
default&#xa0;
defaultWorkforce 
default&#xa0;
default1
default6
default.
default              
defaultThe people who work in children’s homes are vitally im
defaultportant to the experience of the children 
defaultand young people living there. 
defaultThe action research that the LGA commissioned OPM to carry out found that workforce development merits further attention. Children’s homes are receiving children and young people with
default increasingly high level or complex needs; strategies for skills development and to avoid burn out could help in matching needs with supply in the medium to long term. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default7
default.
default              
defaultChildren’s home staff and managers in both 
defaultcouncil
default and independent provision 
defaultsaid
default 
defaultthey are struggling to meet the needs of increasingly complex and challenging children and young people placed in their care. The skills, knowledge and experience of the children’s home workforce is clearly linked to the range and quality services availabl
defaulte and the extent to which a provider can deliver effectively against an offer to commissioners. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default8
default.
default              
defaultLocal authorities who took part in the research are concerned about burn-out and loss of experienced staff from children’s homes as pressure on the 
defaultfrontline increases. Ofsted is clear that home managers are one of the most important factors in determining the quality of care delivered, so this should be of great concern. Whilst the work at national level will help build a picture of current workforce
default qualifications, capabilities and skills gaps, local authorities want to find ways to encourage peer support, the sharing of effective practice and career progression.
default&#xa0;
default1
default9
default.
default              
defaultIn requiring all care staff 
defaultto
default achieve the minimum necessary qualification within t
defaultwo years of starting employment, t
defaulthere could be a risk that existing experienced employees without the necessary qualification might be reluctant to take the steps to acquire a new qualification and leave. The regulation should be sensitive about this so t
defaulthat levels of experience can be shown to be equivalent to the relevant qualification. This might require a more elaborate assessment process however which may increase the costs to home operators and therefore to councils as commissioners. The qualificatio
defaultn process will inevitably take people out of work for periods which may lead to staffing over-stretch; again, the system needs to be sensitive and flexible to cope with realities on the ground.
default&#xa0;
default20
default.
default              
defaultWe agree with 
defaultthe proposal that from 2018 requirement for
default candidates for registered manager posts to have achieved the necessary management qualification prior to appointment,
default but since it is widely acknowledged that the managerial position is vital for quality assurance we would query why this would be delayed 
defaultbeyond the 2017 date for more junior staff.
default&#xa0;
default21
default.
default              
defaultWe agree with
default p
defaultroposals
default&#xa0;
defaultthat
default&#xa0;
defaulthomes should only be able to operate for as shortest time as possible without a registered manager (or locum) being appointed and 
defaultOfsted
default being informed; 
defaultmoreover, new homes shoul
defaultd not be able to open without a registered manager identified as part of the registration process.  
default&#xa0;
default22
default.
default              
defaultAll regulations of this sort are bound to increase the costs of commissioning a service but it is widely agreed that the quality of these vital servic
defaultes needs to improve. It will be important to improve the accuracy of cost estimates for these requirements and to monitor actual costs carefully so that resources can be properly 
defaultchannelled
default to meet these new national requirements.
default&#xa0;
defaultChildren who go missing
default&#xa0;
default2
default3
default.
default              
defaultProtecting children is one of the most important things
default that councils do and t
defaulthe evidence has become increasingly clear that going missing can be an indicator of something affecting the safety and wellbeing of children. In particular, the link between
default going missing and the risk of child sexual exploitation is now widely accepted. Other agencies, in particular the police, but also health services and voluntary organisations
default,
default have an important role to play and it is essential that all have processes in p
defaultlace to work together in instances where children go missing.  
default&#xa0;
default2
default4
default.
default              
defaultThe LGA welcomes the streamlining of 
defaultthe
default statutory guidance, to ensure that it is clear and easy to use for all those involved and does not inc
defaultlude unnecessary prescription. 
defaultThis flexibil
defaultity is essential, in order that agencies can take the most appropriate action based on existing local services and arrangements.  
default&#xa0;
default2
default5
default.
default              
defaultWe welcome 
defaultthe proposed 
defaultrequirements on children’s homes to have policies on preventing children going missing, although
default it is important that there is flexibility as to the content, so that local service provision and arrangeme
defaultnts can be suitably reflected. 
defaultLocal authorities have safeguarding responsibilities for children who are placed in their area by other authorities an
defaultd we would therefore support the policies being agreed with the local authority in the area where the home is located
default as well as the police
default. Given the multi-agency nature of the issue, the Local Safeguarding Children Board would appear to be the sensible p
defaultlace for policies to be discussed and agreed. This would also help to ensure a consistent approach across a local area.
default&#xa0;
default2
default6
default.
default              
defaultWhen there is concern due to a child going missing, consideration needs to be given to whether the placement is the right one and w
defaulthether the placement can be provided in such a way that the child becomes more settled.
default&#xa0;
defaultA formal review of the care plan takes place if a whole new set of needs are identified; therefore, the proposed duty on the registered person of a children’s home to f
defaultormally request a review of the child’s care plan in cases where children are persistently missing from placement
default 
defaultcould be disproportionate
default in some instances. 
defaultFor example, it might be that the residential staff need advice on how best to care for a young p
defaulterson with particular needs. 
default&#xa0;
default2
default7
default.
default              
defaultThe ‘plan’ (residential care) might be the right ‘plan’ but it might be the wrong placement; a review would not necessarily be called because a placement changes.
default&#xa0;
default Alternative, more proportionate options could include the registered manager having the powe
defaultr to ask for a meeting with the social worker and others involved in delivering the care plan to consider the issue of the young person being missing from home, or the power to request a formal response from the local authority setting out what action is b
defaulteing taken and why as a result of the concern being raised.  This would enable the action to be tailored to the specific problem, whether a formal review, a meeting between professionals, or advice provided to staff. 
default&#xa0;
default2
default8
default.
default              
defaultFurthermore, we believe that the 
defaultproposal that a review meeting should be convened in circumstances where any or all of the area authority, registered manager of a children’s home or fostering service, foster 
defaultcarer
default, parent
default&#xa0;
defaultrequest that a review is needed, in response to concerns that a ch
defaultild is at risk
default, i
defaultntroduces unnecessary prescription and runs counter to the principle in the Munro review
default,
default to increase professionalism and 
defaultuse of 
defaultprofessional judgement.  
default&#xa0;
defaultRemoving references to child prostitution from legislation
default&#xa0;
default2
default9
default.
default              
defaultWe strongly support
default 
defaultthe removal of 
defaultreferences to prostitution and replacing these with the term sexual exploitation. Using the term prostitution indicates that children have a choice or that they are consenting to their own abuse.  It belies the fact that exploitation is a s
defaulterious form of abuse and a crime.  
